The paper focuses on the development of a visual analytics system for detecting and labeling social spambots on Twitter. This involves the use of techniques such as sentiment analysis, topic modeling, and dimensionality reduction. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which deals with the analysis and modeling of social networks. 

The paper also discusses the challenges of detecting spambots, which involves the use of machine learning and data mining techniques. This suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category, which deals with the development of secure systems and the detection of malicious activities. 

The use of visualization techniques and interactive analysis also suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.SD (Software Engineering) sub-category, which deals with the development of software tools and techniques. 

The paper also discusses the use of sentiment analysis and topic modeling, which are techniques commonly used in the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category, which deals with the retrieval and analysis of information from large datasets. 

Finally, the paper discusses the user study conducted to evaluate the performance of the VASSL system, which suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) sub-category, which deals with the design and evaluation of interactive systems.
